<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="subsec-1-2-2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <p>A handy way of figuring out the truth value of something is by building a <term>truth table</term>. Below is a table that shows the truth value of <m>P\implies Q</m></p>

    <figure>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P\implies Q</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      
    </figure>
    <p>To build a table like this on your own, it is easiest to start with the one element (P) and go from there. In the example above, the second column shows the possible values of Q when P is true, and when P is false, and the third column builds on that. Let's see another example.</p>

    <figure>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell>~<m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(</m>~<m>P)\implies Q</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      
    </figure>
    <p>Now let's look at a more "complicated" example:</p>
          
    <figure>
        <tabular halign="center">
          <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P\vee Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P\wedge Q</m></cell>
            <cell>~<m>(P\wedge Q)</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(P\vee Q)\wedge [</m>~<m>(P\wedge Q)]</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
            <cell>T</cell>
            <cell>F</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      
    </figure>

</section>